"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-leon-marchand-gold-medal-france-phelps-record-physical-gifts-paris\", \"text\": \"PARIS \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 The roars were deafening, rattling around La D\\u00c3\\u00a9fense Arena, pressing down on eardrums, vibrating the air. The screaming voices were urging the man of the hour, the day, the Olympiad, to go faster in pursuit of glory.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt sounded like a soccer stadium,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d said Carson Foster, an American tasked with trying to chase the man of the hour, the day, the Olympiad.  This wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t a soccer stadium; it was a swim meet, and it was the loudest four minutes I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve ever heard in 32 years of covering the sport. It was a Frenchman in France, enjoying the biggest Olympic home-pool advantage since Australian Ian Thorpe \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThorpedo\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d in Sydney in 2000. And L\\u00c3\\u00a9on Marchand met the moment.  Every time Marchand rose above the water\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s surface to take a breath during the breastroke leg of the 400-meter individual medley, some 14,000 fans bellowed at him in unison. It was a rhythmic exhortation, pushing the 22-year-old from Toulouse further and further ahead in the third leg of the race, until it wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t even a race anymore.\\u00c2  All that remained over the final 100 meters was a coronation, and the pursuit of his own history. Marchand\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s time of 4:02.95 took down Michael Phelps\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 Olympic record in the most difficult event, but did not quite break his own world record of 4:02.50. (We appear to have the dreaded Slow Pool on our hands at these Olympics.)\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cMy objective was to break a record tonight,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Marchand said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI felt really good. In the last [lap], I took advantage of the crowd because I knew I was ahead, I knew I was an Olympic champion.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  That narrow miss of the record he set last year hardly mattered at the end. Marchand\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gold-medal rout of silver medalist Tomoyuki Matsushita of Japan and bronze medalist Foster delivered on expectations that were set Eiffel Tower-high last year, when he first erased Phelps\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 400 IM world record. Coached by Bob Bowman, the same man who mentored Phelps to a record 28 Olympic medals (23 of them gold), Marchand is now officially the biggest star of the Paris Olympics.  The son of two French Olympic swimmers had toleave the country to maximize his potential, inviting himself to swim for Bowman at Arizona State with a cold-call email. But France fully embraced its expatriate aquaman for these games, elevating him to a Victor Wembanyama or Kylian Mbapp\\u00c3\\u00a9 level of celebrity.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI felt really proud to be myself, and to be also French,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Marchand said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was an amazing time for me, and I was really living in the moment.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The evening began with a festival atmosphere outside the area. French fans were chanting, singing and drinking outside La D\\u00c3\\u00a9fense Arena, waiting for the doors to open. They wore masks emblazoned with Marchand\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s face. Or they carried cutout images of him. One little boy wore his Arizona State swim cap.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAl-lez! L\\u00c3\\u00a9-on! Al-lez! L\\u00c3\\u00a9-on! Al-lez, L\\u00c3\\u00a9-on!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d they chanted.  And then they went inside and made more noise. The entire arena sang a French song in unison 12 minutes before the race. They cheered over the top of Deep Purple\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSmoke on the Water,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d then they watched Marchand smoke the water.  They were on their feet and bellowing from the moment Marchand was introduced until after he touched the wall. When the Frenchman straddled the lane line and thrust his hands in the air, they exulted. When he blew them a kiss, they swooned. When he leaped from the pool and placed both hands on his hips, a conqueror looking down at his aquatic kingdom, they roared.  Then they sang the French national anthem with Marchand, who briefly allowed his eyelids to flutter closed while on the podium. He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a perfect swimming machine\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094quite literally made for this moment\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094but he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a human being who was savoring the perfect confluence of time and place and accomplishment.  Bob Bowman isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t one to get caught up in technical terms, so he describes the swimming study as \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009chow your boat floats.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d In more precise language, part of theNeptune Project in Francewas creating a hydrodynamic profile of its elite swimmers\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094essentially measuring how easily they go through the water.  One swimmer measured off the charts in the yearlong study: L\\u00c3\\u00a9on Marchand.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe has the best results I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve ever seen,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Ricardo Peterson, one of the data analysts who worked on the project. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBy far.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Simply put, Marchand is built to slice through a pool like nobody else. Swimmers have long talked about a vague-but-real \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cfeel for the water,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and the French study may actually have quantified it.  Peterson and his colleagues identified \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cpassive and active drag\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d affecting swimmers. Passive drag measured them in the gliding position primarily on starts and turns\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094when they are streamlined and not actively moving their limbs. Active drag measured them during actual swimming movements. Marchand was elite in both categories.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s almost like natural selection,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Peterson says of his body type. Legs create more drag than torso because they don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t float, and Peterson says Marchand is blessed with a larger and longer torso and shorter legs\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094much like Michael Phelps. Via nature or nurture, he also has an optimal swimming posture.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe has a uniform body, in the streamline position, from shoulders to feet,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Peterson observes. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s an outlier in terms of morphological characteristics.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  When not gliding, Marchand is both ferocity and poetry in motion. His stroke technique is impeccable, and his underwater work might be the best in the world at this point. In the crucial 15 meters at the starts and turns when swimmers are allowed to be submerged, Marchand blows away his competition. There are greater drag forces on the surface than beneath it, so the work down below is critical.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cL\\u00c3\\u00a9on is much, much better than anyone else underwater,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Peterson says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHis movement underwater is very symmetric, and he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s able to sustain his underwaters for a very long time. He can reduce drag by staying underwater. Comparable to other swimmers, he has a lower energy cost.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  That helps explain how he can do what he does without overwhelming physical prowess. Marchand on dry land is an unremarkable sight; he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s about 6'2\\\" and not overly muscled. His handshake is as fluid as water\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094which, come to think of it, might be telling.  Some of this may simply come down to good genes. Marchand is the son of two French Olympic swimmers, Xavier and C\\u00c3\\u00a9line, which certainly helps account for body type and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cfeel.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d But the other element that has to be present in addition to physical gifts is work ethic. Marchand has that in abundance.  After selling himself to Bowman in a cold-call email, Marchand showed up at Arizona State as an accomplished swimmer but not a superstar\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099d competed in the Tokyo Olympics but wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t a medal threat. Nobody could have easily foreseen what he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s become. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the work he put in at the Mona Plummer Aquatic Center at ASU, under the tutelage of arguably the greatest IM coach of all time, that turned him the sensation he is today at age 22.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe just pushes himself to the limit, and past the limit a lot of times,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Hubie Kos, who swam with Marchand at Arizona State and will continue to do so at Texas, where Bowman recently moved. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI trained with a lot of people who don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t show the same kind of potential in practice that they do in meets, but L\\u00c3\\u00a9on is quite the opposite. He has crazy practices.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Adds another ASU swimmer, Grant House: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cEverybody breaks down at our practices eventually, and I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve only seen him break down about three times in three years. When he does it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Oh my gosh, he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s human after all.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  L\\u00c3\\u00a9on Marchand was standing underneath a maze of scaffolding underneath the stands in the arena when someone handed him a phone. He pressed it to his right ear. On the line: French president Emmanuel Macron.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat was a first for me,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Marchand said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe called me and told me that he was watching the final with all his family and everyone was kind of screaming on the phone.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  It might not be his last presidential call of the coming week. Marchand still has up to three races ahead: the 200 IM, 200 breaststroke and 200 butterfly. The 400 IM is his unbeatable event, but he will have a chance to win all the others, and certainly will be a medal threat in each.  The challenge now will be returning to earth and returning to the grind of this meet. Marchand has Monday off, but will dive back in with both the 200 fly and 200 breaststroke preliminaries and semifinals on Tuesday\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094a killer double, but one he has been planning to take on for a while now. The final in those events will be Wednesday, and then the 200 IM rounds begin on Thursday.  If anyone has been coached for this multitasking, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Marchand. Bowman guided Phelps through incredible workloads and understands the other elements that come into play\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094all the press conferences, the drug testing, the warmups and warmdowns, and recovery work. Managing everything outside the swimming is where the Olympics becomes a real beast.  Marchand was sufficiently ready for this moment that Bowman didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t have to do much pre-race coaching. There was nothing to discuss. If there was a message to convey, it could be boiled down to:Go be L\\u00c3\\u00a9on.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t think we had to talk about the race,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Marchand said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe were both ready to do what we had to do. I think before the race he was telling me to relax and stay happy. This was a pretty good chance for me to be home at the Olympics.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been a long time since a swimmer enjoyed this kind of home-pool advantage, if ever. France\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s L\\u00c3\\u00a9on Love-In was an audio bombardment that will echo through the rest of these Olympics.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Pat Forde is a senior writer for Sports Illustrated who covers college football and college basketball as well as the Olympics and horse racing. He cohosts the College Football Enquirer podcast and is a football analyst on the Big Ten Network. He previously worked for Yahoo Sports, ESPN and The (Louisville) Courier-Journal. Forde has won 28 Associated Press Sports Editors writing contest awards, has been published three times in the Best American Sports Writing book series, and was nominated for the 1990 Pulitzer Prize. A past president of the U.S. Basketball Writers Association and member of the Football Writers Association of America, he lives in Louisville with his wife. They have three children, all of whom were collegiate swimmers.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"